ng with an accessible overview of the rise of entrepreneurialism in Canada, it features portraits of 61 individuals organized thematically. Here, readers will meet a variety of seminal characters: the merchants of the first trading posts and the commercial empire of the St. Lawrence; the industrialists of the Maritimes, Central Canada, and the West; the railway builders and urban developers; and everyone in between.Bringing to the fore new Dictionary of Canadian Biography research on the rise of Canadian entrepreneurialism - one of the least explored yet most important themes in our history - this book showcases Canada&apos;s long-running tradition of business innovation and growth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBusinesspeoplezCanadavBiography. 0aEntrepreneurshipzCanadaxHistory. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBélanger, Réal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnglish, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266232240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442662322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442662322.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK